close_symbols: Definitions (numeric values) of the error-code set used by OS_FileSys_Initialize
All project call sites of OS_initfs (references/callers) and any call sites that examine its return value (comparisons against the three error codes)
explanation:
- OS_FileSys_Initialize: The branch in OS_initfs depends entirely on the return value of this function. To decide if the conditional and subsequent assignment are ever executed (and therefore not dead) we must know every return value OS_FileSys_Initialize can produce and under what conditions.

- OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE: The if-condition tests for this constant. We need its definition to determine (a) whether OS_FileSys_Initialize can return this value and (b) whether it is numerically distinct from OS_FS_ERR_DEVICE_NOT_FREE (if it is identical/aliased the assignment could be redundant).

- OS_ERR_NO_FREE_IDS: Same reasons as above — it appears in the conditional and we must know if it can be returned and whether it is distinct from the mapped value.

- OS_FS_ERR_DEVICE_NOT_FREE: This is the target value assigned inside the conditional. Knowing its numeric value (and whether it equals one of the other codes) is required to detect whether the assignment changes program behavior or is redundant.

- Definitions (numeric values) of the error-code set used by OS_FileSys_Initialize: Beyond the three named macros, the full set (or header where they are defined) is needed to detect aliases, conditional definitions, or configuration-time remapping that could make the conditional or assignment effective/ineffective.

- All project call sites of OS_initfs (references/callers) and any call sites that examine its return value (comparisons against the three error codes): MISRA dead-code analysis must consider program-wide behaviour. If external callers rely on OS_initfs producing the legacy codes (or rely on the mapping to OS_FS_ERR_DEVICE_NOT_FREE), removing the mapping would change observable behaviour. Conversely, if OS_initfs is never called, the whole function may be dead. Therefore you must inspect all callers and their checks of the return value to determine if the conditional/assignment or the function itself constitute dead code.
